The family of former Liberian president Charles Taylor expressed concerns over the imbalance in legal representation, with the prosecution having more senior counsels than the defense.
They also criticized the court's violation of Taylor's privacy rights by installing surveillance cameras during attorney-client meetings.
Taylor's lawyers demanded more time to prepare for the trial, citing insufficient resources compared to the prosecution.
Witnesses were hesitant to testify due to fear of UN sanctions.
The trial, moved to The Hague for security reasons, faced delays as the defense sought additional legal support.
